  "prompt": "What is XS3 code?",
  "response": "XS3 code, also known as Excess-3 code, is a binary-coded decimal (BCD) code used in digital systems, primarily for arithmetic operations. It is a non-weighted code that is created by adding 3 to each decimal digit and then converting the result to its corresponding 4-bit binary form.\n\nHere\u2019s how XS3 code works:\n\n1. Add 3 to the decimal digit you want to represent.\n2. Convert the result to its 4-bit binary equivalent.\n\nFor example, converting the decimal number 5 into XS3 code involves:\n\n1. Adding 3 to 5, which results in 8.\n2. Converting 8 to binary, which is 1000.\n\nTherefore, the XS3 code for the decimal digit 5 is 1000.\n\nXS3 code helps to simplify the design of digital circuits, especially for decimal arithmetic operations, by eliminating the need for complex binary-to-decimal conversion steps.",
